During twenty years which he spent in the town of* St. Iago, in the service of the Spaniard J uan Diaz Ca'eperlahachin, he evinced much probity‚ and even piety. Every year, in the last week of Lent, did he publicly mangle his back with a bloody scourge3 but after having effected his escape, and got back to his countrymen, he became the scourge of the Spaniards, and shedding torrents of their blood, obtained a high renown amongst his own people‚ to whom his knowledge of roads and places rendered him eminently useful; for, in expeditions having the slaughter of the Spa- niards for their object, no man discharged the offices of scout and leader more gloriously or more willingly than he.
